<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-19T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-19T03:00:00-05:00" n="595" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11701: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief of the United States Asiatic
                                Fleet</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Yarnell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Named
                                Operations</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi></persName>)<note n="25" xml:id="d595fn25">Copy
                                transmitted to the Department by the Navy Department.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-19T16:00:00+08:00">December 19, 1937—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 19—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>0119. An officer Japanese Navy informed Admiral Holt<note n="26" xml:id="d595fn26">Commanding British naval forces in the
                                Yangtze.</note> at Nanking that the channels through Mudfort and
                            Kiangyin barriers have been made solely for use of the Japanese forces
                            and not for the use of neutral shipping and that passage of H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Ladybird</hi>, U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Oahu</hi>
                            and others of that convoy cannot be taken as a precedent.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>